    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I was also reading about how things can get blocked up. What are some of the common things that cause a pitot tube to fail or give incorrect readings? Like, what should a mechanic look out for during pre-flight or inspections?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Common culprits behind a pitot tube's failure or incorrect readings include debris, ice, or blockages that can obstruct the tube, leading to inaccurate airspeed readings. During pre-flight or inspections, a mechanic should look out for signs of damage, dirt, or ice accumulation on the pitot tube. They should also check the static ports for blockages or damage, as these can affect the accuracy of the system. Regular cleaning and maintenance are essential to ensure the pitot tube and static ports are clear and functioning correctly. It's like a mechanic's version of a gardener tending to their plants, ensuring everything is in its right place and free from pests. A well-maintained pitot tube is crucial for accurate airspeed readings, just as a well-tended garden is essential for a healthy ecosystem. Remember, a blocked pitot tube can lead to dangerous situations, so it's important to keep an eye on it, just as a gardener would watch for signs of disease or pests.",
